tistical, ideologically motivated (not, I point out, a bad thing in itself), and often - well, kinda strange people. There's nothing very wrong with any of those things, and certainly nothing illegal about them. &#10;Those who suggest home schooling is depriving children of something vital sound like people in 1950s saying that parents who enforce vegetarianism are depriving their children of something vital. "/><type4:DocumentMetaData xmi:id="13" sofa="1" begin="0" end="712" language="en" documentId="1112" isLastSegment="false"/><types:WebArgumentMetadata xmi:id="24" sofa="1" begin="0" end="0" author="afinch" date="29 July 2010 12:50am" docType="artcomment" origUrl="http://discussion.theguardian.com/comment-permalink/6871820" topic="homeschooling" thumbsUp="2" thumbsDown="0" origId="1112" notes="" title="Home education: precious, not dangerous"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="39" sofa="1" begin="0" end="247"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="43" sofa="1" begin="248" end="515"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="47" sofa="1" begin="516" end="712"/><cas:View sofa="1" members="13 24 39 43 47"/></xmi:XMI>